04173nam a22005415i 9780520921634DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209216347 a10.1525/97805209216342doi  a(DE-B1597)648755  a(OCoLC)1419790011  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aREL0700002bisacsh1 aLeyerle, Blake, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTheatrical Shows and Ascetic Lives :bJohn Chrysostom's Attack on Spiritual Marriage /cBlake Leyerle; ed. by Blake Leyerle. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (259 p.) :b1 line illustration  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tList of Abbreviations -- t1 Introduction -- t2 The Late Antique Theater -- t3 John Chrysostom's View of the Theater -- t4 Spiritual Marriage -- t5 Ridiculous Men -- t6 Frightful Women -- t7 John Chrysostom's Role -- t8 Conclusion -- tAppendix. Dating the Treatises -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book provides an original and rewarding context for understanding the prolific fourth-century Christian theologian John Chrysostom and the religious and social world in which he lived. Blake Leyerle analyzes two highly rhetorical treatises by this early church father attacking the phenomenon of "spiritual marriage." Spiritual marriage was an ascetic practice with a long history in which a man and a woman lived together in an intimate relationship without sex. What begins as an analysis of Chrysostom's attack on spiritual marriage becomes a broad investigation into Chrysostom's life and work, the practice of spiritual marriage itself, the role of the theater in late antique city life, and the early history of Christianity. Though thoroughly grounded in the texts themselves and in the cultural history of late antiquity, this study breaks new ground with its focus on issues of rhetoric, sexuality, and power. Leyerle argues that Chrysostom used images and tropes drawn from the theater to persuade religious men and women that spiritual marriage was wrong. In addition to her analysis of the significance of the rhetorical strategies used by Chrysostom, Leyerle gives a thorough discussion of the role of the theater in late antiquity, particularly in Antioch, one of the gems among late antique cities. She also discusses gender in the context of late antique religion, shedding new light on early Christian attitudes toward sexuality. Throughout Leyerle weaves an ongoing conversation with contemporary theory in film and gender studies that gives her study an important analytic dimension.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aChristianity. 4aGeneral. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh1 aLeyerle, Blake, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052021558040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092163440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520921634423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520921634/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles